A history professor before he turned to politics, he is survived by seven of his eight children, one daughter died tragically at 31, and his wife Arlene.

Crane represented Chicago's far northwest suburbs for 35 years and was the longest-serving House Republican when he was defeated in 2004 by Democrat and then-political newcomer Melissa Bean.

Crane also made an unsuccessful run for the Republican presidential nomination in 1980, losing out to the eventual winner, Ronald Reagan, who would go on to become the politician most closely associated with the modern conservative movement.

But Crane had touted what he saw as the virtue of smaller government going back to the 1960s, spelling out his vision of a stripped down, low-tax federal government in his 1976 book, 'The Sum of Good Government.'

'Phil was conservative before it was cool to be conservative,' said Eric Elk, a congressional aide to Crane through much of the 1990s.

